-----------------------------# Snake game #--------------------------------------
from turtle import Turtle, Screen
import random
import time

# This line imports two important things from the 'turtle' library:
# 1. Turtle: This is like a pen that can draw shapes and move on the screen. We'll use it to create the snake and food.
# 2. Screen: This is the window where our game will appear. We can set its size, color, and title.
from turtle import Turtle, Screen
import random
import time

# We create the game screen here. Think of it as your canvas.
screen = Screen()
# We set the size of the game window to 600 pixels wide and 600 pixels high.
screen.setup(width=600, height=600)
# We set the background color of the screen to black.
screen.bgcolor("black")
# We set the title that appears at the top of the game window to "Snake game".
screen.title("Snake game")
# This is a special command that turns off the automatic updating of the screen.
# We do this so we can control when things appear to move, making the animation smoother.
screen.tracer(0)

# This is a list of starting positions for the snake's body parts.
# Each item in the list is a coordinate (x, y).
# The first coordinate (0, 0) is where the snake's head will start.
# The others are for the body segments that follow.
starting_position = [(0, 0), (-20, 0), (-40, 0)]
# This is an empty list where we will store all the parts (segments) of the snake.
segments = []

# This loop goes through each starting position we defined.
for position in starting_position:
    # For each position, we create a new 'Turtle' object.
    # Think of this as creating one square for the snake.
    new_segment = Turtle("square")
    # We set the color of this square to white.
    new_segment.color("white")
    # When a turtle moves, it can draw a line. We don't want the snake to draw lines as it moves,
    # so we lift the pen up.
    new_segment.penup()
    # We move the new square to its starting position on the screen.
    new_segment.goto(position)
    # We add this new square (which is a segment of the snake) to our 'segments' list.
    segments.append(new_segment)

# This is a flag that tells us if the game is still running.
game_is_on = True
# This loop will continue to run as long as the 'game_is_on' flag is true.
while game_is_on:
    # This command updates the screen to show the changes we've made (like moving the snake).
    # Because we turned off automatic updates with 'screen.tracer(0)', we need to do this manually.
    screen.update()
    # This pauses the game for a short amount of time (0.1 seconds).
    # This controls the speed of the snake. A smaller number makes it faster.
    time.sleep(0.1)
    # This loop goes through our list of snake segments, but it starts from the last segment
    # and goes backwards to the second segment (index 1). We don't move the head in this loop.
    for seg_num in range(len(segments) - 1, 0, -1):
        # For each segment (except the head), we get the x-coordinate of the segment in front of it.
        new_x = segments[seg_num - 1].xcor()
        # We also get the y-coordinate of the segment in front of it.
        new_y = segments[seg_num - 1].ycor()
        # We then move the current segment to the position where the segment in front of it was.
        # This makes the snake look like it's moving as a whole.
        segments[seg_num].goto(new_x, new_y)
    # After moving all the body segments, we move the head of the snake forward by 20 units.
    segments[0].forward(20)
    # This line makes the head of the snake turn 90 degrees to the left.
    # Because this is inside the main game loop, the snake will keep turning left continuously.
    segments[0].left(90)

# This line keeps the game window open until you click on it to close it.
# It's important to have this at the end of your script.
# screen.exitonclick()
```

**Simple Explanation of the Logic:**

1.  **Setting up the Stage:** We create a window (the screen) and give it a color and title. We also get our "pen" ready (the `Turtle`).

2.  **Building the Snake:** We start by creating three white squares and placing them next to each other horizontally. These are the initial parts of our snake. We keep track of these parts in a list called `segments`.

3.  **Making it Move (Body):** Inside the game loop, for every part of the snake *except the head*, we tell it to move to the position where the part in front of it was in the previous step. This makes the body follow the head.

4.  **Making it Move (Head):** We then tell the head of the snake to move forward a little bit.

5.  **Turning the Head:** In each step of the game, we also tell the head of the snake to turn 90 degrees to the left. This is why the snake in this code will just keep moving in a circle.

6.  **Keeping it Smooth:** We use `time.sleep()` to make the movement visible and not too fast. We also use `screen.update()` to show the changes we've made to the snake's position on the screen.

**In simple terms, the code creates a snake made of squares. In each step of the game, every part of the snake moves to where the part in front of it was, and the head moves forward and turns left.**
